"1310–1360":"1310–1360","1326–Female":"1326–Deceased","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1326":"1326","1348":"1348","1425":"1425","8 August 1422":"8 August 1422","1356":"1356","1422":"1422","1410":"1410","1310":"1310","about 1348":"about 1348","about 1410":"about 1410","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Salford, Lancashire, England":"Salford, Lancashire, England","Radcliffe, Lancashire, England":"Radcliffe, Lancashire, England","Wymersley, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Radcliffe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Ratliff  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ratliff","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from one or more of the places so named, such as Radcliffe (Lancashire), Radcliffe on Trent and Ratcliffe on Soar (both Nottinghamshire), Radclive (Buckinghamshire), Ratcliffe Culey and Ratcliffe on the Wreake (both Leicestershire), Ratclyffe in Clyst Hydon, Ratcliffes in Thorverton, and Ratcliffes in Broad Clyst (all Devon), Ratcliff in Stepney (Middlesex), and Rackley in Compton Bishop (Somerset). The placenames derive from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>clif</i> ‘cliff, bank, steep slope’ (see also   Rutley  ). A family of the name <i>Radcliffe</i> trace their descent from Sir Nicholas <i>de Radclyffe</i>. He is said to have been a knight who held the major of Radcliffe in Lancashire and served Roger de Poitou, Baron de Marsey in the 11th century."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Radcliffe was born about 1348, in Radcliffe, Lancashire, England, his father, Lord William de Radcliffe of Todmorden, was 40 and his mother, Ellen de Langfield, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Agnes Greenacres. He died on 8 August 1422, in Salford, Lancashire, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1348–8 August 1422":"umbes 1348–8. august 1422","1340–1425":"1340–1425","1348–1422":"1348–1422","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1360–1385":"1360–1385","1362–Female":"1362–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1326":"1326","1348":"1348","1425":"1425","8 August 1422":"8. august 1422","1356":"1356","1422":"1422","1410":"1410","1310":"1310","about 1348":"umbes 1348","about 1410":"umbes 1410","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Salford, Lancashire, England":"Salford, Lancashire, England","Radcliffe, Lancashire, England":"Radcliffe, Lancashire, England","Wymersley, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1348–8 August 1422":"noin 1348–8. elokuuta 1422","1340–1425":